SIMPLE: tortuous
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tortuous
<hw>Tor"tu*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>tortuos</ets>, L. <ets>tortuosus</ets>, fr. <ets>tortus</ets> a
twisting, winding, fr. <ets>torquere</ets>, <ets>tortum</ets>, to twist:
cf. F. <ets>tortueux</ets>. See <er>Torture</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Bent in different directions; wreathed; twisted; winding; <as>as, a
<ex>tortuous</ex> train; a <ex>tortuous</ex> leaf or
corolla</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The badger made his dark and <qex>tortuous</qex> hole on the side
of every hill where the copsewood grew thick.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Fig.: Deviating from rectitude; indirect; erroneous;
deceitful.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That course became somewhat less<qex>tortuous</qex>, when the
battle of the Boyne had cowed the spirit of the Jakobites.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Injurious: tortious.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Astrol.)</fld> <def>Oblique; -- applied to the six
signs of the zodiac (from Capricorn to Gemini) which ascend most rapidly
and obliquely.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Skeat.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Infortunate ascendent <qex>tortuous</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>--<wordforms><wf>Tor"tu*ous*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> --
<wf>Tor"tu*ous*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Torturable</ent>⟦br⟧
